column8: predicted_definition

column3: A dendritic cell that captures antigens in a lung and migrates to a lymph node or to the spleen to activate T cells.
column8: A type of dendritic cell that is found in the lungs and has the ability to migrate.

column3: An ON bipolar cell type with dendrites selectively contacting S-cones.
column8: A type of retinal bipolar neuron that is excited by blue light and inhibited by red light. These cells are involved in the transmission of visual signals from photoreceptor cells to other retinal neurons.

column3: An OFF calbindin-positive bipolar cell that has a large dendritic field and stratifies narrowly close to the middle of the inner plexiform layer. Its axon terminal is characterized by regularly branching and varicose processes resembling beads on a string. Most of DB3a contacts with cones are triad-associated.
column8: A type of diffuse bipolar 3a cell that is characterized by its electrical properties and morphology.

column3: A spermatid in an early stage of maturation that has a round morphology and is transcriptionally active.
column8: An early stage in the development of a sperm cell, which is produced by meiosis.

column2: airway submucosal gland duct basal cell
column3: A basal cell that is part of a duct of an airway submucosal gland.
column8: A submucosal gland found in a respiratory tract that produces mucus and has ducts leading to the airway. It also contains basal cells.

column3: A fibroblast that is part of the fibrous layer of the perichondrium. This cell is responsible for collagen fiber production.
column8: A fibroblast that is part of the outer fibrous layer of perichondrium.

column3: An ON bipolar cell with a small dendritic tree that forms most of the central (invaginating) elements opposite the synaptic ribbon at the cone triad.
column8: A type of midget bipolar cell found in the retina that receives input from cone photoreceptors and is involved in processing brightness information.

column3: A medium spiny neuron that exhibits transcriptional divergence from direct and indirect spiny projection neurons, for example, enrichment in Casz1, Otof, Cacng5 and Pcdh8 noted in mice. Whilst in general medium spiny neurons have been found to be differentially distributed across the basal ganglia, the eccentric medium spiny neuron cell type has been found to be more evenly distributed throughout cerebral nuclei.
column8: An inhibitory, GABAergic projection neuron in the striatum that integrates glutamatergic signals arising from the cerebral cortex and thalamus.

column3: A medium spiny neuron that expresses both DRD1 and DRD2 and is part of an extra-striosomal part of dorsal striatum.
column8: A medium spiny neuron that expresses both D1 and D2 dopamine receptors, located in the dorsal striatum.

column3: An alveolar macrophage that expresses metallothionein.
column8: An alveolar macrophage that expresses the protein metallothionein.

column3: An ON diffuse bipolar cell that has a large dendritic field and large axon terminals, which show little or no overlap. This cell predominantly connects to narrow thorny ganglion cells.
column8: A type of retinal bipolar neuron that is sensitive to light and has connections with photoreceptor cells.

column3: A macrophage that is part of the lung connective tissue (pulmonary interstitium). This cell performs tissue remodeling and contributes to barrier immunity through antigen presentation.
column8: A macrophage that is part of the connective tissue in a lung.

column3: An alveolar macrophage that expresses CCL3.
column8: An alveolar macrophage that expresses CCL3 chemokine.

column3: A glial precursor cell that generates oligodendrocytes and type-1 and type-2 astrocytes. It has been shown in some mammals that this cell type may express A2B5, nestin, FGFR-1, FGFR-2, FGFR-3, PLP, and DM-20 antigens. Unlike oligodendrocyte precursor cell, it does not initially express PDGFR-alpha and can differentiate into both type-1 and type-2 astrocytes.
column8: A type of glial cell that can differentiate into neurons, astrocytes and oligodendrocytes.

column2: lung resident memory CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell
column3: An alpha-beta CD8 T cell that resides in the lung.
column8: A lung resident memory CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell that is part of the lung.

column2: mucus secreting cell of bronchus submucosal gland
column3: A mucus secreting cell of a submucosal gland of the bronchus.
column8: A mucus secreting cell located in a bronchus submucosal gland.

column3: A neuron that releases catecholamine as a neurotransmitter.
column8: A neuron that uses catecholamines as a vesicular neurotransmitter.

column3: An ON diffuse bipolar cell that predominantly connects to ON parasol cells and lateral amacrine cells.
column8: A type of retinal bipolar neuron that is activated by light and has connections with photoreceptor cells.

column3: A ciliated cell of the endometrial glandular epithelium.
column8: A glandular epithelial cell of the endometrium that has cilia.

column3: An epithelial cell part of respiratory tract epithelium that is a precursor of a multi-ciliated cell. This cell actively amplifies centrioles, a required step for multiciliogenesis.
column8: An epithelial cell that is part of the respiratory tract [Automatically generated definition].

column3: A megakaryocyte that is resident in the lung connective tissue.
column8: Megakaryocytes in the lung connective tissue.

column3: A taste receptor cell that is part of a taste bud of a tongue.
column8: A cell that is part of a taste bud on the tongue and detects chemical signals from food to initiate the sense of taste.

column3: A DRD2-expressing medium spiny neuron that is part of a matrix compartment of dorsal striatum.
column8: A type of indirect pathway medium spiny neuron that expresses dopamine D2 receptors.

column3: An OFF bipolar cell that is fovea-specific and expresses FEZF1, NXPH1 and NXPH2.
column8: A type of bipolar cell in the retina that is sensitive to light and located near the ganglion cells.

column3: A myofibroblast that is part of an alveoli during alveolarization. The contractile force of this cell elongates the secondary crest, while producing a framework of elastin and tenascin. During the maturation of the septa, secondary crest myofibroblasts, together with matrix fibroblasts, secrete metalloproteinases and other ECM‚Äêremodeling proteins to thin the septal tip ECM. The secondary crest myofibroblast continues producing elastin, eventually undergoing apoptosis during adulthood.
column8: A myofibroblast cell that is part of the secondary crest during lung development and participates in alveoli formation.

column3: An OFF diffuse bipolar cell that predominantly connects to ON parasol cells and lateral amacrine cells. This cell contains a large number of synaptic ribbons and a small axon arbor area.
column8: A type of retinal bipolar neuron found in the outer plexiform layer and having connections with photoreceptor cells.

column3: A urothelial cell that is terminally differentiated and part of the urothelial apical surface that forms the high-resistance barrier of urothelium. Umbrella cells have been described as the largest of urothelial cell types, highly polarized, and, in some species, multinucleated. In the relaxed state, these cells form a dome-shaped structure at the apical pole and can also cover multiple underlying intermediate cells, leading to the name umbrella cells. In contrast, these cells flatten when the bladder is filled.
column8: An umbrella cell is a type of epithelial cell that is part of the urinary bladder urothelium. These cells are located in the submucosa and are larger than other urothelial cells, giving them an umbrella-like appearance under a microscope.

column2: nucleus accumbens shell and olfactory tubercle D2 medium spiny neuron
column3: A DRD2-expressing medium spiny neuron that is part of a nucleus accumbens shell or olfactory tubercle.
column8: A medium spiny neuron that expresses dopamine type 2 receptors and projects to the external globus pallidus. It is located in the nucleus accumbens shell, which is part of the ventral striatum.

column3: A respiratory epithelial cell with topographic nuclear position in between the basal and luminal cell of the airway epithelium. This non-basal, intermediate cell has limited proliferative capacity, ultrastructural features of basal cells and no defined features of the typically differentiated cellular phenotypes.
column8: A respiratory suprabasal cell found in the epithelium of the respiratory tract.

column3: Glial cell that provides support to the enteric nervous system. It is involved in enteric neurotransmission, in maintaining the integrity of the mucosal barrier of the gut and serves as a link between the nervous and immune systems of the gut. In enteric nerve strands, glial processes ensheath multiaxonal bundles which distinguishes enteric glia from all other peripheral glia. Ultrastructurally, the most conspicuous trait of an enteroglial cell is the presence of 10 nm filaments, which criss-cross the cell body, form axial bundles in the processes and appear to firmly anchor the cells to the ganglionic surfaces. Similar to astrocytes, their main constituent is glial fibrillary acidic protein (GFAP).

column2: lung resident memory CD8-positive, CD103-positive, alpha-beta T cell
column3: A lung resident memory CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell that is CD103-positive.
column8: A lung resident memory CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cell that has the phenotype of being CD103-positive and expressing IntegrinAlphaE on its plasma membrane.

column3: A ciliated cell of the respiratory system. Ciliated cells are present in airway epithelium.
column8: A respiratory tract epithelial cell that bears vibratile cilia on the free surface.

column2: CD24-positive, CD-133-positive, vimentin-positive proximal tubular cell
column3: A CD24-positive, CD-133-positive, vimentin-positive cell found scattered throughout a renal proximal tubule and that may participate in tubular regeneration. Compared to other proximal tubular cell types, this cell contains less cytoplasm, fewer mitochondria and no brush border.
column8: A proximal tubular epithelial cell that is CD24-positive, CD133-positive and vimentin-positive.

column3: An OFF calbindin-negative bipolar cell that has a large dendritic field and stratifies narrowly close to the middle of the inner plexiform layer. Its axon terminal is characterized by regularly branching and varicose processes resembling beads on a string. Most of DB3b contacts with cones are non-triad-associated.
column8: A type of diffuse bipolar cell that is part of the retina's ON and OFF pathways.

column3: A ciliated cell of the endometrial epithelium. The cilia of this cell type help move mucus from glandular tissue of the endometrium.
column8: An epithelial cell of the endometrium that has cilia.

column3: An OFF bipolar cell with a small dendritic tree that provides most of the triad-associated basal (flat) contacts at cone pedicles.
column8: A type of ON and OFF bipolar cells that have a small soma, short dendrites, and axons with myelinated segments.

column3: A DRD1-expressing medium spiny neuron that is part of a matrix compartment of dorsal striatum.
column8: A direct pathway medium spiny neuron that expresses dopamine type 1 receptors and projects to the globus pallidus internus or the substantia nigra pars reticulata.

column2: lung resident memory CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell
column3: An alpha-beta CD4 T cell that resides in the lung.
column8: A lung resident memory CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cell that is differentiated into a memory T cell.

column3: A smooth muscle cell that is part of a bronchiole.
column8: A smooth muscle cell that is part of a bronchiole.

column2: mucus secreting cell of tracheobronchial tree submucosal gland
column3: A mucus secreting cell of a submucosal gland of the tracheobronchial tree.
column8: A mucus secreting cell that is part of a tracheobronchial submucosal gland.

column3: A DRD2-expressing medium spiny neuron that is part of a striosome of dorsal striatum.
column8: A type of indirect pathway medium spiny neuron located in the striatum that expresses dopamine D2 receptors.

column3: A DRD1-expressing, medium spiny neuron-like granule cell that is part of an Island of Calleja.
column8: One of the seven small groups of granule cells in the polymorph layer of the olfactory tubercle and one large group, the insula magna, which lies along the border between septum, nucleus accumbens and nucleus of the diagonal band.

column3: A star-shaped glial cell that is part of some retina. This cell links neurons to blood vessels and may provide structural and physiological support to optic nerve head axons.
column8: A retinal astrocyte.

column3: A urothelial cell that is part of the regenerative layer(s) of cells directly superficial to basal cells in urothelium. The layer of intermediate cells in the urothelium ranges from one to several layers thick depending on the species with intermediate cells attached to adjacent cell layers and one another via desmosomes.
column8: An intermediate cell that is part of the urothelium.

column3: A perichondrial fibroblast that is part of the lung.
column8: A perichondrial fibroblast that is part of lung.

column3: An OFF diffuse bipolar cell that makes synaptic contact with both L/M and S-cone photoreceptors and only minimal contact with rod photoreceptors.
column8: A type of retinal bipolar neuron found in the outer plexiform layer that depolarizes during a light to dark transition.

column3: A horse-specific, highly invasive trophoblast cell that invades the endometrium where it forms endometrial cups.
column8: A type of trophoblast cell that is derived from the chorion and forms part of the placental bed.

column3: Precursor of type II pneumocyte. These cells do not have lamellar bodies, which are a marker of type II pneumocyte maturity.
column8: A type I pneumocyte that is a precursor to the mature type II pneumocyte.

column3: A spermatid in a late stage of maturation that has an elongated morphology and is transcriptionally inert when the acrosome is fully developed.
column8: A late stage of sperm development, characterized by the formation of a structure called the acrosome.

column3: A dental pulp cell that possesses stem-cell-like qualities, including self-renewal capability and multi-lineage differentiation.
column8: A stem cell that is part of dental pulp.
